{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Bahtoo Memorial Stadium | nickname = | image = Bahtoo Stadium.JPG | image_size = 200px | location = [[Mandalay]], [[Myanmar]] | coordinates = {{coord|21|59|00|N|96|6|00|E|region:MM_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | opened = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator =Yadanarbon FC | surface = [[Grass]] | Constructor = | construction_cost = | architect = | former_names = | nicknames = Bahtoo Stadium | tenants = [[Yadanabon FC]] | seating_capacity = 17,000<ref name="ws">{{cite web | url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/asia/countries/myanmar.shtml | title=Stadiums in Myanmar | accessdate=2008-11-24 | publisher=World Stadiums}}</ref> | dimensions = }}
'''Bahtoo Memorial Stadium''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]], located in downtown [[Mandalay]], [[Myanmar]].<ref name="ws"/> Its address is the corner of 71sr st and 30th st beside of the Bahtoo Sport Centre.
== Overview == Named after revolutionary Colonel Bahtoo, the 17,000 seat stadium was the largest stadium in Upper Myanmar before the construction of [[Mandalarthiri Stadium|the Mandalarthiri Stadium]] and the home stadium of [[Yadanabon FC]] of the [[Myanmar National League]] (MNL).
Bahtoo Stadium also hosts other local and regional football tournaments. It was the venue for the 2006 [[Myanmar Grand Royal Challenge Cup]], an international football tournament.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200612/24/eng20061224_335471.html | title=Myanmar triumphs in three-nation soccer tournament | accessdate=2008-11-24 | date=2006-12-24 | publisher=Xinhua News}}</ref>
